term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) if you need a refresher.) This, one hopes, will=
 be the culmination of his long and tortured effort to appoint a permanent =
newsroom chief and move the storied D.C. institution beyond the woes of yet=
 another year from hell: ongoing financial losses, rudderless strategy, sta=
ff uprisings, endorsement-gate, etcetera.

If you recall, the last time Lewis attempted an editorial restructuring, th=
e feculence hit the fan. In June, he tried to appoint his old friend and Fl=
eet Street veteran Rob Winnett to the position=E2=80=94while inelegantly tr=
ying to transition then-executive editor Sally Buzbee to the nebulous third=
 newsroom, where she would oversee soft-focus, social-friendly content to g=
row the
Post=E2=80=99s audience. Instead, Buzbee self-defenestrated, the staff turn=
ed on Lewis and Winnett over a litany of ethical concerns, real or perceive=
d, and Winnett eventually opted to stay home in London. Amid all this, Lewi=
s made an eleventh-hour appeal to Wall Street Journal veteran Matt Murray t=
o steady the ship as the newsroom=E2=80=99s temporary leader.

In the process, Lewis also articulated a few unvarnished truths about the P=
ost=E2=80=99s business: =E2=80=9CYour audience has halved in recent years,=
=E2=80=9D he told his journalists. =E2=80=9CPeople are not reading your stu=
ff. I can=E2=80=99t sugarcoat it anymore.=E2=80=9D This memorable admonishm=
ent stressed the urgency of the Post=E2=80=99s challenges, but it also fore=
shadowed a new tone and tenor from the front office, and a new mandate for =
the notoriously disgruntled staff: Get with the program, or get out. Indeed=
, when the Post=E2=80=99s union protested Lewis=E2=80=99s recent return-to-=
office mandate, he told them he=E2=80=99d
kindly accept the resignations of any W.F.H. dead-enders. And as I noted la=
st month, neither he nor Bezos were terribly bothered by the departure of m=
orally righteous journalists who protested the decision to forgo a presiden=
tial endorsement of Kamala Harris. As with any business transformation, the=
y probably welcomed the turnover.

In a best-case scenario, Lewis would use the anointment of a new executive =
editor as an opportunity to further nudge the Post out of its era of inerti=
a. This new leader would not merely be tasked with overseeing a newsroom, b=
ut also establishing a new mandate for the coverage, and, indeed, even a ne=
w identity for the paper itself=E2=80=94one divorced not just from the rudd=
erlessness of the Buzbee era, but also from the =E2=80=9CDemocracy Dies in =
Darkness=E2=80=9D posturing of the Baron era, and perhaps with a little les=
s nostalgia for Bradlee and Graham and Woodward and Bernstein.

Presumably, this new mandate would align with Bezos=E2=80=99s own desire to=
 restore the Post to its former place as the paper of record for official W=
ashington and, as I=E2=80=99ve noted before, as an at least semi-nonpartisa=
n organization servicing all Americans, rather than a regional edition of t=
he Times political report servicing anxious liberals. At best, the Post mig=
ht once again establish itself as a compelling and authoritative source on =
the culture of power and influence in Washington, with its finger on the pu=
lse of not just the White House and Capitol Hill but also Cleveland Park an=
d Kalorama. For now, Lewis would at least like someone who can inspire staf=
f to come into the newsroom and file a little more often.

The challenge, of course, is finding that leader among a particularly limit=
ed talent pool of editors who are actually willing to inherit all the afore=
mentioned challenges, and whose identity won=E2=80=99t
establish a second theater of war. Earlier this fall, executive recruitment=
 firm Spencer Stuart approached dozens of candidates on the Post=E2=80=99s =
behalf, including Times managing editor Carolyn Ryan, Cliff Levy, and other=
 members of the Times masthead=E2=80=94the majority of whom did not engage =
in anything beyond preliminary talks. Levy, who now oversees the Times=E2=
=80=99s Athletic and Wirecutter, did engage beyond preliminary talks, and i=
s among the handful of candidates who interviewed with Lewis and submitted =
memos outlining their near- and long-term visions for the newsroom. There a=
re other external candidates as well, though I don=E2=80=99t yet have their=
 names.

Meanwhile, as previously noted, there are two internal candidates vying for=
 the position: Murray, the acting executive editor, and managing editor Mat=
ea Gold, herself a 12-year veteran of the paper. Both have their strengths =
and weaknesses=E2=80=94don=E2=80=99t we all=E2=80=94but,
crucially, neither is seen as the kind of change agent that Lewis would pre=
sumably favor to lead the newsroom. Frankly, they=E2=80=99re just hometown =
Cliff Levy types=E2=80=94well-pedigreed and smart, yes and of course, but i=
nstitutionalists without track records of innovation and risk-taking. Long =
before his current sinecure essentially serving as the Wirecutter and Athle=
tic=E2=80=99s liaisons to the mothership, Levy ran the ill-fated NYT Now ap=
p project, where he liked to point out the novel quirk of a Times product s=
aying =E2=80=9Chello=E2=80=9D to its readers. Like others, he=E2=80=99s a m=
ulti-Pulitzer winner who commands respect and has been promoted out of powe=
r.

Murray, who served as the Journal=E2=80=99s editor-in-chief when Lewis was =
its publisher, may be his preferred candidate of the two, but many in the n=
ewsroom are unsurprisingly said to favor their longtime colleague. And, ala=
s, he may have to settle on one or the other. But, boy, would that seem lik=
